## vercel.json Build Environment Variables Configuration

### Current Recommendation (2025)

Vercel no longer recommends using the legacy method for environment variables in vercel.json. Instead, they recommend you migrate your environment variables to the Environment Variables UI.

### Legacy vercel.json Configuration Example

You may have configured the `env` and `build.env` legacy properties in a vercel.json file:

```json
{
  "env": {
    "MY_KEY": "this is the value",
    "SECRET": "@my-secret-name"
  },
  "build": {
    "env": {
      "MY_KEY": "this is the value",
      "SECRET": "@my-secret-name"
    }
  }
}
```

### Another Example with Builds and Routes

The vercel.json file in a backend project is used to configure deployment settings for Vercel. This file allows you to specify various options like build settings, routes, redirects, and environment variables.

```json
{
  "version": 2,
  "builds": [
    { "src": "server.js", "use": "@vercel/node" }
  ],
  "routes": [
    { "src": "/api/(.*)", "dest": "server.js" }
  ],
  "env": {
    "DATABASE_URL": "@database_url",
    "API_KEY": "@api_key"
  }
}
```

### Key Points About Environment Variables

Vercel Environment Variables are key-value pairs configured outside your source code that change depending on the environment (local/development, pre-production, or production).(no content)These values can be used during builds or inside functions to read API keys, connect to your database, and more. You can add Environment Variables to your site through Project Settings.(no content)Values are encrypted at rest and permission to view values can be restricted based on your role.(no content)Some frontend frameworks like Next.js require environment variable access on client side to be explicitly defined through the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix.

### Dynamic Build Commands Using Environment Variables

For certain workflows, it may be useful to execute different scripts based on specific environments or branch names. To do this, you'll create a vercel.sh file in your repository that your Build Command uses to run conditional logic.(no content)You can use conditional logic like `if [[ $VERCEL_ENV == "production" ]]` to run a script according to the environment. You can adjust this to use any other System Environment Variables on Vercel.

### Important Note

Migrating to the Environment Variables UI will help you avoid errors when implementing your environment variables.


